Graphs of logarithms

In this section we consider logarithmic functions in more detail. We shall concentrate primarily on the functions \(\log x\) (i.e. to base \(10\)) and \(\ln x\) (i.e. to base \(e\)). We shall see that the functions \(y=\log x\) and \(y=\ln x\) have similar characteristics. Note that we can never choose \(x\) as a negative number since \(10^y\) and \(e^y\) are each always positive. The graphs of \(y=\log x\) and \(y=\ln x\) are shown in the figure below.

Logarithmic and exponential functions

From the graphs we see that both functions are one-to-one so each has an inverse - the inverse function of \(\log_ax\) is \(a^x\). In fact the natural logarithm function \(f(x)= \ln(x)\) is defined to be the inverse of the exponential function \(y = e^x\). Geometrically this tells us that the graph of \(y = \log_a x\), \(a > 0, a \not=1\) is the reflection of the graph \(y=a^x\) in the line \(y=x\). Algebraically, this means that \[ e^{\ln(x)} = x\ \ \text{for all}\ x > 0\quad \text{and} \quad \ln\left(e^x\right) = x \ \ \text{for all}\ x. \] The first equation only holds for all \(x>0\) because \(\ln\) is not defined for negative numbers, i.e. its domain is \(0 < x < \infty\). This directly corresponds to the fact that the range of \(e^x\) is \(0 < y < \infty\).
